@node sect0 "Name"
samerase - erase a SAMDOS file or files 
@endnode

@node sect1 "Synopsis"
@{b}samerase@{ub} [ @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} ] samdosfile [ samdosfiles... ] 
@endnode

@node sect2 "Description"
@{i}Samerase@{ui} erases a file or files on a SAMDOS diskette.  The filenames will be displayed as they are erased.  Wildcard characters are allowed in the filenames.  The use of wildcards or spaces will require the names to be enclosed in quotes to protect them from the shell. @{i}Samerase@{ui} may be used to erase files from a disk image rather than a real floppy by setting the environment variable SAMDISKFILE to the name of the image file or by supplying the @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} flag.  If used this flag must be written first on the command line. It may be abbreviated to @{b}-disk @{ub}@{i}file.@{ui} 

If the disk is in MasterDOS format then full pathnames may be used. See @{i}samtools@{ui}(1) for further information about directories. If a supplied filename names a directory on a MasterDOS disk then the directory will be removed only if it is empty. 

You are not allowed to erase any file named '' or, on a MasterDOS disk, a name ending with the slash character (or the currently defined separator for directories).  If the name really is blank then specify the name as a single space character. 


@endnode

@node sect3 "See Also"
samtools(1) 
@endnode

@node sect4 "Bugs"
@{i}Samerase@{ui} will blindly erase read-only files without asking for verification. 
@endnode
